the global registry via side-effect imports. Library\nconsumers therefore get the same default behaviour as the CLI\nwithout having to enumerate each internal/formats/* package\nthemselves; a consumer who wants a stripped-down set builds their\nown binary that imports the formats they want directly, bypassing\nthis convenience package.\n\nTwelve orchestrator unit tests cover: every sentinel error arm\n(nil reader, nil writer, unknown tokenizer, unknown format,\nunknown output, unknown strip-envelope); the end-to-end gotest\npath against an inline fixture; explicit-format-beats-detect;\nzero-events ExitCode=1 mapping; context cancellation (no\ngoroutine leak); ndjson streaming output (first line begins with\nthe schema-version sentinel); markdown FenceLang propagation; and\nMinSeverity propagation into ParseOpts (the generic format drops\nor keeps a warning depending on the configured floor).\n\nTwo integration tests in test/integration/ guard the layering\ninvariant. TestPublicAPI_NoLeakedInternalImports parses every .go\nfile directly under pkg/distill/ and asserts every internal/*\nimport is either a documented type-alias target (internal/event,\ninternal/formats) or a known side-effect import for registry\nregistration. Adding a new direct dependency on, say,\ninternal/pipeline from pkg/distill/distill.go would now fail the\nbuild. TestPublicAPI_OrchestratorIsPrivate confirms the\norchestrator sits under pkg/distill/internal/ so a future refactor\nthat hoisted it to a non-internal path would surface in CI.\n\ninternal/output.LineCounter gains atomic protection on its\ntrailing-line flag. Pre-M15 the only consumer was the CLI, which\nread LineCounter.Lines() inside Sink.Sink() — by then the parser\ngoroutine had already finished its last Read() because the Sink\nruns strictly after the source. M15 changes the access pattern:\nthe orchestrator's Run.Wait() reads Lines() after pipeline.Run\nreturns, which under context cancellation can race the still-\nrunning parser goroutine (Pipeline.Run's relay returns on\nctx.Done() without waiting for the source to drain). The race\ndetector flagged this on Windows CI on the first run. The fix\npromotes the trailing-line bool to atomic.Int32 so concurrent\nRead()/Lines() access is well-defined regardless of pipeline\nshutdown ordering. The newline-counter field was already atomic.\nEOF\nwc -l /var/folders/_4/hgrfrlss2ql9mmz8rb1_psh00000gn/T/opencode/pr/m15_4_msg.txt",
